<article>
    <h1>NANA MATSUOKA, 23</h1>
    <h2>So&#xAD;cial en&#xAD;tre&#xAD;pre&#xAD;neur, Ja&#xAD;pan</h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201219/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-19"><time>2020-12-19</time></a>
        - <span>SPECIAL REPORT</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>While in high school, Ms Nana Matsuoka learnt about how poor di­etary habits af­fected peo­ple in parts of the world.</p>
    <p>In 2017, she started Wely (for­merly Well­nesone Ja­pan), a food ed­u­ca­tion and nu­tri­tion im­prove­ment firm fo­cus­ing on Viet­nam, where she had seen a trend of poor health among chil­dren in ur­ban ar­eas as a re­sult of over­nu­tri­tion.</p>
    <p>Her firm is de­vel­op­ing a sys­tem called MoGuCare that al­lows nurs­ery work­ers to digi­tise the pa­per­work, such as weight and body tem­per­a­ture records, mak­ing it eas­ier to vi­su­alise the health sta­tus of a child and no­tice any change. She plans to ex­pand it to Thai­land, Malaysia and Africa.</p>
    <p>This year, Forbes Ja­pan named her one of 30 young peo­ple who will change the world.</p>
    <p>Ms Matsuoka told The Straits Times: “You can’t change the world alone, but with friends who share your thoughts, you can surely change the world for the bet­ter.”</p>

